Return String from rust_to_c.

In preparation for handling pointers.

Update examples in README.

Split the single example into many little examples.
Give up on trying to infer the output file for now.
Slight rearrange to DRY off the code.
Setup cargo for an executable crate.
Remove TODOs and make GH issues.
Ensure all spans refer to the correct thing.

Fix compilation error.

c_out could not be assigned inside a closure.

Use try! in even more places!

If .bump() fails it already calls parser.fatal and .bump_and_get() only fails if
bump fails so we can just use try on those two methods.
Allow enums and structs to omit final comma.
Use better method for getting the path.
Implement basic support for enums and structs.
Allow the library path to be read from `Cargo.toml`.
Create directories before trying to write header.
Rewrite tests to use new API.
Allow header to be compiled from a string.
Allow header to be compiled into a string.

Convert library to syntex.

Now compiles on stable and correctly parses basic files.
Correct use of ie to eg.

Allow api to be inside a module.

As long as the api is exposed to the top level.

Use strings for paths and names.

This gives specifying the output directory and file name is now much more
intuitive, `dir = "/path/to/out/dir"` and `file = "file_name.ext"`
respectively.

Use cargo-readme.

Allows us to keep all info in the source.
Test function pointers with no named args.

Revert "Implement opaque structs."

This reverts commit 54a18d32560c16ab0d6a1898fecf5e1fc146985e.

Private structs can not be used in public type signatures so there is literally
no way to use this feature as it was implemented.
Handle path types more gracefully ... I think.

Instantiate buffer in check_crate.

Since it's not needed anywhere else.

Instantiate buffer in check_crate.

Since it's not needed anywhere else.

Give each item it's own mini buffer.

This prevents leaving a header file in a corrupt state if an item is discovered
to be non-compatible halfway through processing.
Note that source file invocation requires nightly.
Emphasise use with stable Rust crates.
Talk about building on stable the using cheddar.

Keep #[allow(...)] attributes as tight as possible.

Just because it's needed in one part of the function doesn't mean you should
stop checking other parts.
Mention using cheddar from the command line.

Rewrite tests section.

The CppHeaderParser issues have now been fixed.

Rewrite rust_to_c to use Ty tokens.

Opens the way for function pointers.
Bump version and publish to crates.

Use and_then.

Removes the need for two unwrap_ors.
Fix race condition caused by setting working dir.

Implement some sort of testing framework.

As hacky as it is.
Write a script for comparing header files.
Actually use clippy, rather than pretending.
Be more clever about default file names.
Avoid allocating so many strings in retrieve_docstring.

Move rusty-cheddar to a lint-based interface.
Allow file to be specifid with plugin args.

Write header to file.

For now just write to cheddar.h in current directory.

Move to a Lint-based technique.

Matches the drop-in based technique almost one-to-one but requires much less
reinventing the wheel.
Remove example since it's not an executable.

The current implementation doesn't recognize the --lib and --bin arguments.

Merge pull request #36 from rillian/osraw

Support std::os::raw variants of libc types.

Remove redundant `test` from test function names.

These are already marked as tests by the cheddar_cmp_test!
macro name, the #[test] attribute it adds to the functions
it creates, and the `test` header the harness prints when
running them.
Verify rejection of non-pathed libc and std::os::raw types.

Hardcode the #[test] attribute.

Merge the (optional) additional attributes into the name argument
to make the parsing unambiguous. Without this the compiler can't
tell if the attribute is the header expression or not.

Support xfail test variants.

Allow passing an extra `xfail` argument to the compile form
of the test macro to verify we reject certain inputs.

This is a little complicated. We can't just insert the
extra #[should_panic] in the xfail case before the expansion
of inner_cheddar_cmp_test!() because attributes do not
attach properly through nested macro expansions. Instead
we must match on the attributes in the inner pattern and
pass them explicitly to each invocation.
Update documention to include std::os::raw types.

Allow comparision with the full module prefix.

Previously we just switched on the first segment on the module
path, which was sufficient to match 'libc' but not qualified
paths like 'std::os::raw'. Turn the segment list back into
a path string and compare on that.

Fixes test_os_raw_types.

Support std::os::raw variants of libc types.

Until the libc crate becomes part of the stable toolchain,
it's nice to have these versions work too for situations
where external crate dependencies are difficult.
Namespace generated enum members with the name of the enum.

Sanitise the identifier used in the include guard.

Macros must be valid C identifiers but since we allow an arbitrary
id to be passed in by the user we can't guarantee this. Also we
can't guarantee that a file name is a valid identifier.
Allow the API to be placed inside any arbitrary module.
Allow custom code to be injected into the header.
Test function pointers as return types.

Allow function pointers to be used as a return type.

Function pointers don't need a name associated with them, they just
need some sort of "inner" which could be a function declaration.

Compartmentalises the compilation. `cheddar::parse` is no longer
responsible for include-guards, includes, or extern declarations.
